@DRSDavidSoft 
I didn't quite understand your question. Transparency levels are only applied when you override them in `settings.json`. If you don't - the patch does nothing. There is nothing to enable in `settings.json`...

@gusbemacbe 
1. I don't see connection between color overriding and blurring.
2. What do you mean by saying "not allowed"?

@DRSDavidSoft
So if I understand you correctly you need this kind of switch to handle the situation when one uses both "normal" and transparency-enabled themes. Because defining `"window.transparencyAlphaSource": "theme"` globally is equivalent to not using any `*.opacity: ...` customizations, as I said.

Now if you use both kinds of themes you would like to have smth. like that in `settings.json`:
```javascript
"workbench.colorCustomizations": {
    // applied to all themes
    "panel.background.opacity": "#000000e0"
    "[MyTransparentTheme]": {
        // not not apply global opacity customizations here
        "window.transparencyAlphaSource": "theme"
    }
}
```
Since strings are not allowed in theme customization, I can define some *special* theme color and special value for it (say, `#00000000`) which would mean `"window.transparencyAlphaSource": "theme"`. But again, we are abusing theme colors to specify non-color values (boolean in this example) and this is not a proper solution.

As for `"window.transparencyAlphaSource": "auto"` I don't think its possible to implement it easily since this requires to check ALL theme colors (including customization) for alpha value before applying ANY color and this would probably kill performance (unless we cache it somehow).

@gusbemacbe
Regarding "not allowed" options: my fault, fixed my fork, try updated branch now.

Regarding blur, if I understand correctly the only thing that can be blurred is background behind main VScode window. This is done by OS/compositor and the PR only instructs it to do so. As I said, my patch has nothing to do with it, you should just use the options @sylveon implemented for your OS. Personally I don't like blur since I use tiling WM so I always see the wallpaper "through" my windows and using blur kind of ruins the aesthetics. By choosing "right" wallpapers and opacity levels I manage to make text always clearly readable.

Now if you talk about blurring some VScode elements behind *other* VScode elements, I'm not sure that's even possible in Electron and most probably out of the scope of this PR. Currently the most annoying example of this are quickpick windows: these are controlled by `sideBar.background` so if you make sidebar transparent then you see editor text through quickpick items text making the later unreadable. Unfortunately I have to solution for that besides making sidebar almost opaque.

